Exploratory Analysis of COVID-19 in New Zealand

Introduction

This project provides an exploratory analysis of the data relating to confirmed cases of COVID-19 in New Zealand as at 29th March, 2020. At this point, there were 552 confirmed cases.

The main motivation for this work is to support researchers and anyone who may be interested in understanding key trends and to ask more and better questions that may support research and eventual elimination of COVID-19.

The data file has been sourced from Ministry of Health

To illustrate by example, below are the details of the top five rows of the data.

Report.Date Sex Age.Group DHB Overseas Last.country.before.NZ Flight.no Departure.date Arrival.date
1 2020-03-29 Male 50 to 59 Auckland Yes 22/03/2020
2 2020-03-29 Female 50 to 59 Auckland Yes 24/03/2020
3 2020-03-29 Male 40 to 49 Auckland
4 2020-03-29 20 to 29 Auckland
5 2020-03-29 Female 20 to 29 Auckland

The purpose of this analysis was to answer the following key questions:

  1. What is the daily trend for confirmed cases?
  2. Exploratory Analysis of key variables and their interactions.
  3. Are there any cluster of variables?

To answer these questions, the following trend analysis was conducted:

  1. Origin of Virus
  2. Distribution by age
  3. Distribution by gender
  4. Distribution by Location
  5. Location versus age, gender and origin
  6. Distribution by age vs gender
  7. Overseas vs sex and age
  8. Distribution by country last visited
  9. Last Country versus age, gender and region
  10. Distribution by Duration since departure
  11. Multiple Correspndence Analysis
  12. Heirarchical Clustering
  13. Hierarchical Clustering on Principal Components
  14. K-Modes Clustering
  15. Factor Analysis

This report is divided according to the three research questions followed by a conclusion.

1. Daily Trend Analysis

The plot below shows the trend for the number of people confirmed to have COVID-19 on a given day. The x axis represents the date and the y axis represents the number confirmed cases.

The graph above shows that the number of confirmed cases has been increasing steeply since the 16th of March.

2. Exploratory Analysis of key variables.

2.1. Origin of Virus

Within the dataset, there are three groups of people.

  1. Cases who reported travelling overseas

  2. Cases who did not travel overseas

  3. Cases who did not report any travel information

The following analysis compares the daily trend for each of these groups.

These results show that majority of the cases have travelled overseas and that cumulatively, the rate at which these cases are being confirmed is increasing exponentially. The curve is showing signs of leveling due to travel restrictions globally.

The number of patients who have not traveled overseas is also showing what appears to be an exponential increase since around the 20th of March. In the event of a community outbreak, this graph should overtake the line for cases who traveled overseas.

2.2. Distribution by age

The following bar chart shows the distribution of the confirmed cases by age

The distribution shows that:

  • a large proportion of cases are between the ages of 20 and 29.
  • over 20% of cases are older than 60 years.
  • less than 10% of patience are below the age of 20.

3. Multivariate Analysis

The results so far have related to some of the key variables and their interaction with some of the other variables.

In this section, we aim to explore the interaction of all the variables within the multi-dimensional space to determine if there are any other insights within the data set.

\(~\)

3.1. Multiple Correspndence Analysis

The Multiple correspondence analysis (MCA) is primarily used for summarising and visualising data with more than two categorical variables. It is a generalised form of principal component analysis for dimensionality reduction when the variables to be analyzed are categorical instead of quantitative.

The goal of MCA is to identify:

  1. A group of individuals with similar profile in their answers to the questions
  2. The associations between variable categories

The scree plot below shows the percentages of inertia explained by each MCA dimension

The variables only explain 20% of the variance within the data with the first 2 dimensions explaining 6%. The remainder of this analysis is based on these two dimensions.

The following two plot shows the correlation of variables against each dimension and the distribution of cases in these dimensions.

The analysis indicates the existence of three clusters and one outlier (Labelled 170).

The following analysis indicates that the two large clusters relate to people who travelled overseas (right hand side) and those who did not (those on the left). The right hand side is also influenced by cases in their 20s and over 50. The left hand side is heavily correlated to cases under 20 years.

Bay of Plenty, Tarawhiti, Whanganui and Lakes DHB are most highly correlated to the overseas group while Southern DHB is correlated to the local group.

The smaller cluster mainly relates to cases in Hawkes Bay from Spain, North America and Cambodia.

The outlier relates to a case reported in Taranaki but Gender and Age are unknown.

The following plots show the distribution of variables in each dimension.

Finally, the following plots show the contribution of variables among each dimension.

\(~\)

3.2. Heirarchical Clustering

Hierarchical clustering aims to build a hierarchy of clusters. We use an Agglomerative algorithmic/bottom-up approach with each observation starting in its own cluster, and pairs of clusters are merged as one moves up the hierarchy.

The following dendogram shows the grouping of individual cases.

The results indicate five potential clusters with a cophentic distance of 0.7443252. The number of cases in each group are as follows.

  • All cases in Group 1 are from overseas
  • Group 2 comprises of cases where it is unknown if the cases were from overseas.
  • Group 3 comprises of females who did not travel overseas.
  • Group 4 comprises of females who travelled overseas.
  • Group 5 comprises of males who did not travel overseas.

\(~\)

3.3. Hierarchical Clustering on Principal Components

The HCPC (Hierarchical Clustering on Principal Components) approach allows us to combine MCA, Hierarchical clustering and partitioning clustering (k-means).

The plots below shows that the optimal number of clusters is four. These are consistent with the results of the MCA.

The table below shows the number of cases per cluster.

Var1 Freq
1 234
2 297
3 20
4 1

The following outputs show some key attributes of each cluster as follows:

Cluster 1

  • Comprises of 234 cases.
  • 97% of cases that did not travel overseas belong to the cluster.
  • All cases where it is unknown whether the individual travelled overseas belongs to the cluster.
  • 66% of cases reported to Southern DHB and 58% of cases reported to Waikato DHB belong to this cluster.
  • 61% of cases in the cluster are females.

3.4. K-Modes Clustering

K-modes uses dissimilarities and modes to identify clusters. A mode is a vector of elements that minimizes the dissimilarities between the vector itself and each object of the data.

The elbow plot below suggests three clusters. The following tables show the number of cases in these clusters and the modes for each of the clusters.

Size of Clusters
cluster Freq
1 240
2 216
3 96

3 Male 30 to 39 Auckland Yes United States of America

3.5. Factor Analysis

We conclude our analysis by extending the dataset with the derived variable “Duration” representing the number of days between date confirmed and date arrived in NZ.

Multiple factor analysis (MFA) is a multivariate data analysis method for summarizing and visualizing a complex data table in which individuals are described by several sets of variables (quantitative and /or qualitative) structured into groups.

The results are not presented below however this also delivered the same clusters as the MCA.

\(-\)

4. Conclussion

The above analysis illustrates a number of different trends within the key variables associated with confirmed COVID-19 cases in New Zealand.

New Zealand recorded their first confirmed case on the 26th of February and went into a complete four-week (Level 4) lockdown on the 26th of March.

This data set represents cases recorded up to the 30th of March and the analysis therefore represents the trends associated with no or very-little infection control programme.

In the next phase of this project, we will extend the results to show the impact of these measures.

We hope that our results are of value to some of our readers.
